<ol>
  <li>
    <h2 id="bayesian-vs-frequentist-perspective-on-interpretation-of-probability">Bayesian VS. Frequentist Perspective on Interpretation of Probability</h2>
  </li>
</ol>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Frequentist:</strong> long term frequency of event happening in recurring experiment</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p><strong>Bayesian:</strong> a measure of belief in confidence about an event happening</p>
    <ul>
      <li>This belief is based on individuals and different observers may come out different beliefs</li>
      <li>Individualsâ€™ different beliefs do not change what the outcome will come out to be</li>
      <li>You gather evidences to form and update beliefs</li>
      <li>Prior Probability: initial belief $P(A)$</li>
      <li>
        <table>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td>Posterior Probability: updated belief given evidences $P(A</td>
              <td>X)$</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

<ol>
  <li>
    <h2 id="why-simulation-methods-and-when">Why Simulation Methods and When</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>(1) Simulation versus Asymptotic Assumed Optimization Methods</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>the latter uses asymptotic assumptions in population properties) for closed-form solutions while the former uses available observed available samples</p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>(2) Concept of Simulation</p>

    <ul>
      <li>you have observed realizations from some target distribution</li>
      <li>you try to build a pseudo-random number generator that mimics the underlying generation process of the observed realization</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>(3) Types of Simulation</p>

    <ul>
      <li>Resampling: bootstrap, jacknife, permutation</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ul>

